To determine the number of destroyed frames, calculate the transmission time of one frame and divide the noise duration by it.

A Gigabit Ethernet LAN transmits at **1 Gbps (125 MB/s)**. A 1000-byte frame (including overhead) takes:
\[
\text{Time} = \frac{1000 \text{ bytes} \times 8 \text{ bits/byte}}{1 \text{ Gbps}} = 8 \text{ μs}
\]
The noise duration is **2 ms (2000 μs)**, so the number of destroyed frames is:
\[
\frac{2000 \text{ μs}}{8 \text{ μs/frame}} = 250 \text{ frames}
\]

